text: I just hope this isn't another kids versus adults thing where all the adults are sh** and the only good guys are everyone under 19. I'm sorry not ALL adults and parents suck. Sure it's a wish fulfillment, I'm sure a good bunch of us millennials will eat this up- but as a teen it never made sense to me, and I did have a horrible time with adult and authority figures too, but even then I knew the trope of "adults = evil" was kinda stupid. Already in the trailer I can see, " the only people who would ever help us, are us." I hope that guy is proven wrong.  PLEASE prove me wrong movie!!! I'm seeing the people who worked on Stranger Things worked on this, and that gives me hope. Thankfully I never read these books in particular, so can someone confirm if that's the thing that happened in them? Maybe the movie is just doing it and the books are great. I may pick em up if that's the case. Add them to my list.

text: For those who are confused. The children in this movie are under five classification and kids with these abilities are put in a certain section which has a unique color of it's own. *Red* Is for those who can control fire. *Yellow* is for those who can control electricity. *Blue*  is for those can  move things with their minds *Green* is for those who are highly intelligent. In this Movie our dear Ruby (the female lead) will disguise herself as being Green so she can hide who she truly is. Which takes us to our final and most powerful ability.  *Orange* The power to control emotions, thoughts, memories. The power to control people's mind.  Edit: I've read the books and they are amazing, hopefully this movie will do it justice.

text: The novels are classic girl-power feminist/SJW fare (even the obligatory "your just a girl" crap no one ever actually does in real life) with rather one dimensional characters. You know the kind that are "think like me and you're "good" disagree and your an evil monster." It has the usual all guys want the main character thing tween girls love. And of course "The Chosen One" thing which to be fair is pretty common in general. Its OK but nothing you haven't read or seen dozens of time already. Tween girls and SJWs (the market for the books) will wet their pants over it the rest will be bored.  Think Hunger Games, The Fifth Wave, Twilight, and any of the other hundreds of tween girl books put out over the last thirty years with the exact same format: Powerful chosen one girl, all guys want her, anyone not subscribing to the authors politics is evil (Oddly the author describes classic tyrannical leftist societies and then claim they are evil conservative capitalist ones... the irony and stupidity abound), the main character is perfect in every way except some little imperfection that just makes her more perfect, guys are always barley functioning neanderthals (except the ones she likes and they are still inferior somehow), some dystopian type thing is going on or will happen if not for the heroines brilliance, emotions, and power saving the day.Etc. etc. etc.

text: I just have to say... I love superhero movies so much and I came across this trailer in my feed. I watched it and thought it was interesting and maybe a superhero movie with a young female lead I can relate with. I looked up the movie and found it was based on a book series and I was overjoyed, since I've been looking for books to read and this met my liking. After reading the other one's quickly, I'm on the third book. This is now my favorite book series. After reading the first book, I went back to see the trailer and it does not serve the book justice. But then again, when does it ever? In all honestly, I can see this at least TV-14, especially when it comes to the second book. This series has so much heart and emotion, like many other books turned into movies. However, even the trailer has some flaws, I look forward to see this movie. I hope it doesn't turn to Divergent and lose sight of what the books are. I hope it doesn't turn into a teen romance rather than a series about Ruby facing her darkness. I hope that the movie makes the book readers as happy as they can be.
